Air quality alert in effect until 10 a.m. Saturday

The Puget Sound Clean Air Agency has extended the air quality alert through 10 a.m. Saturday. The agency continued to encourage people to remain indoors as much as possible until the alert is lifted. It added:

“We may see some improvement to the north near Puget Sound today as clean ocean air pushes through the strait. Further clearing will happen more broadly with the arrival of rain starting early tomorrow morning and continuing into Saturday. At this time, we don't expect more smoke through the middle of next week.”

Monitor air quality: https://bit.ly/2ZB3zSY and https://bit.ly/32uSdlo

Wildfire smoke info: https://bit.ly/337uo24

Health guidance: https://bit.ly/3jZw9oQ

post_text: Grab and Go School Meals are fresh, healthy and full of flavor! Our awesome school kitchen staff used the school garden kale in smoothies made in our new VitaMix blender. They also used the school garden basil to make Pesto and put in chicken pesto wraps. Pea shoots, lettuce, turnips, spinach and kale were mixed for the tasty salads. Thank you to our Vitamix Donors!!! The fundraiser was hosted by the South Whidbey Schools foundation at the chefs dinner that was held last spring and an individual donor paid for the entire vita mix. Thank you for the wonderful donation. If your child needs school meals, please go to our website for more information at https://www.sw.wednet.edu/communication/news/what_s_new/grab_and_go_meals

post_text: Back to school at South Whidbey in limited hybrid mode began today. The first group of kindergarteners came to school for a meet and greet to find a fun outdoor classroom. Today they learned some classroom routines, made new friends and even made first day crowns! The kindergarteners came ready to learn and full of enthusiasm. The outdoor space was great and conducive to social distancing. I'm not sure who was more joyful - students, staff, or parents! Thank you to Todd Brager and his son who worked with our maintenance director, JJ, creating the beautiful Orca and the gate! The rest of our students are learning remotely whether through our teachers, our parent partnership program (SWAP), our virtual learning program (SWVL) or mixture. We would love to see and share your remote learning photos. Please send them to communications@sw.wednet.edu.

More smoke to pour in tomorrow

Look carefully at this satellite picture. See that super massive cloud of smoke outside of California and Oregon? The wind is changing direction and that's coming your way tomorrow. You have today to prepare. Let your family and friends know. Go shopping for any essentials today. If you don't have to go out tomorrow, stay home.

See air quality forecasts at http://wasmoke.blogspot.com

More information on the difference between symptoms from smoke exposure and COVID-19 at https://www.cdc.gov/disasters/covid-19/wildfire_smoke_covid-19

More information to protect yourself from smoke at http://doh.wa.gov/smokefromfires

On August 18, the Island County Board of Health passed a motion that limits outdoor recreation and sporting activities to 10 people or less, unless a safety plan is submitted to the Island County Health Officer with a request for a waiver to increase the number of people up to the Governor’s limit.

The waiver would allow the group size to be increased up to the Governor’s Modified Phase 3 limit of 50 people or fewer (subject to change by the Governor’s Office), with the following requirements for teams:

• Limited to 1 event involving (or with) one opposing team in 7 calendar days
• No tournaments
• No teams or players from another county

Submit safety plans for a waiver to:
pubhealth@islandcountywa.gov

For additional information:

Island County Public Health – www.islandcountywa.gov/Health/Pages/COVID-19.aspx
Call Center # 360.678.2301, Monday through Friday, 8:00am – 4:30pm

WA State Coronavirus Response (COVID-19) – https://coronavirus.wa.

Health Alert! Youth who use vapes, cigarettes or both are at higher risk for COVID infection

The Snohomish Health District points to a recent study which surveyed youth and young adults age 13-24 found that those who ever used vapes were five times more likely to be diagnosed with COVID than those who didn’t use vapes; and teens who used vapes and cigarettes (dual use) were seven times more likely to be diagnosed with COVID than those who used no tobacco products.
https://www.jahonline.org/article/S1054-139X(20)30399-2/fulltext

Snohomish Health District
August 18 at 10:27 AM ·

You’ve likely seen the case rate per 100,000 reported here for Snohomish County. But why do we look at the case rate per 100,000? Case rates give us a way to measure disease and compare to other areas because it adjusts for differences in population.

A reported increase in the population of Snohomish County contributed slightly to a decrease in the case rate this week because we are now calculating based on a higher number of people. The population change accounts for about one fewer case in the rates (73.7 cases per 100,000 with the new population estimate vs. 74.8 if the latest case rates were calculated with the previous population).

post_text:
August 31 is the deadline to apply for K-12 Pandemic EBT school meal assistance.

Any student in grades K-12 in Washington state who was eligible for free or reduced-price school meals last year is eligible to receive Pandemic EBT, a benefit of up to $399 per student. Families must complete a simple application through the Washington State Dept. of Social and Health Services (DSHS) by August 31, 2020. Pandemic EBT is available regardless of citizenship or immigration status and is not considered a public charge.

Read more about program details here: https://www.dshs.wa.gov/os/office-communications/media-release/washington-families-get-help-buy-food-during-school-closures

Apply online at https://www.washingtonconnection.org/home/

Island County Public Health
August 4 at 8:14 AM ·

The Washington State Broadband Office and state Public Works Board last week launched a comprehensive mapping initiative to identify gaps in high-speed internet service and areas of broadband infrastructure needs. This is part of the state’s effort to ensure universal broadband access in Washington by 2024.
The first step is for Washington residents to perform a one-minute access and speed survey found at https://www.commerce.wa.gov/building-infrastructure/washington-statewide-broadband-act/.
Using the easy-to-follow instructions and a simple link, anyone can complete the speed test at home using any computer or mobile device.

School will be back in session this fall, but learning will look different than it did before the COVID-19 pandemic.
The health and safety of students and staff is our top priority in addition to providing quality education.

South Whidbey School district leaders continue to work with the Island County Public Health regarding the number of cases in our community and when it is safe to gradually expand to in-person education, as is recommended for areas at the moderate COVID-19 activity level.

The SWSD plans for Fall 2020 are available online at https://sw.wednet.edu/UserFiles/Servers/Server_465749/File/Health/Coronavirus/2020-08-04-Sup-letter-Fall-Reopening.pdf

All citizens are invited to nominate candidates for this position, provided that the nominees are registered voters in South Whidbey and who reside within the South Whidbey School District.

Application Process: Applicants must submit by July 31, 2020
- An application form
- A one page summary on why you want to be a school board member and what qualifications you have to be an effective school board member.

Join us an serve the children of your community today!

Please join Helen Price Johnson, Island County Commissioner and Tim Callison, Mayor of Langley
on Wednesday, July 22nd at 5:00 p.m. for a virtual Town Hall to discuss County collaboration with local law enforcement agencies and a COVID-19 response update.

Q&A to follow.

UPCOMING TOWN HALL MEETINGS:

Island County Public Health
July 16 at 3:20 PM ·

Gov. Inslee announced today that due to the increase in COVID-19 activity across the state gathering restrictions for counties currently in Phase 3 will drop from 50 to no more than 10 people per week outside of their households. He also prohibited indoor and outdoor live entertainment.
During the week of June 26-July 2, the state averaged 629 new COVID-19 cases each day. This is the highest rate of COVID-19 since the pandemic began.
To slow the spread in our community, continue to wear a face covering in public spaces, maintain physical distancing and practice good hand hygiene. If transmission continues to rise the state may reinstitute tighter restrictions.

Join the SWSD School Board and Make a Difference for our Children!

Share your wisdom and knowledge. Help shape the future for our children…serve on the South Whidbey School Board!

The South Whidbey School District has a vacancy for an interested parent or citizen to serve on the School Board of Directors as an at large member. All citizens are invited to nominate candidates for this position, provided that the nominees are registered voters in South Whidbey and who reside within the South Whidbey School District.

Term will expire November 2021.

Application Process: Applicants must submit by July 31, 2020

An application form (available online at https://www.sw.wednet.edu/communication/news/what_s_new/school_board_director_position)

A one page summary on why you want to be a school board member and what qualifications you have to be an effective school board member.

Board Applications and Director District Boundaries and MAP are available on the District web-site: www.sw.wednet.edu or https://www.sw.wednet.edu/school_board

Google is launching the Grow with Google initiative to help people get the skills they need to get a job or grow their business through a new suite of Google Career Certificates that will help Americans get qualifications in high-paying high-growth job fields—no college degree required. Google will fund 100,000 need-based scholarships and Google will consider their new career certificates as equivalent of a four-year degree for related roles. They are also committing $10 million in job training Google.org grants for communities across America.

The Joint Information Center has published a brief social media video containing some travel guidance during Phase 2. It pays to know the facts before booking a trip, and to remember that remaining near home is one of the best strategies at this time for reducing the spread of COVID-19. The video addresses several questions we’ve received in recent weeks, including limited access to testing with rapid results. Detailed travel advice also is available from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention: https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/

What is R.A.C.E?

Readiness To Learn
July 2 at 6:33 AM ·

Readiness to Learn's R.A.C.E. (Real Actions Create Equity) was formed in the spring of 2017 to educate ourselves and our community about effective responses to racial and ethnic biases. We raise awareness of the existence of systemic inequity and create safe spaces for people impacted by these injustices.

Check out our introduction video called What is R.A.C.E? Subscribe to our YouTube channel and stay tuned for more videos, including interviews with our 2020 Equity Inclusion and Diversity Award recipients-Jennifer Gandarias, Sarah Gillett, Laura Spear, Debra Davies-Vogel, Micheal Swenson and Susie Richards.

Learn more at https://www.readinesstolearn.org/race
Readiness To Learn South Whidbey Community Center South Whidbey School District Goosefoot

Red Cross Offers Virtual Care for Families Who Have Lost Loved Ones to COVID-19. In order to provide support to families and communities who have suffered loss as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic, the American Red Cross has developed a Virtual Family Assistance Center (VFAC). People can visit redcross.org/VFAC to access this resource with special virtual programs, information, referrals and services to support families in need. The VFAC will also connect people to other community resources that may be provided when available. People without internet access can call toll-free 833-492-0094 for help.

This is an incredibly difficult time for everyone, but especially for those who have lost a loved one due to COVID-19. The Red Cross, in collaboration with our partners, is here to provide compassion and support as they grieve.

Support Available for Managing Stress During COVID-19

Do you know anyone who needs support due to stress from COVID-19? Washington Listens provides nonclinical support to people experiencing elevated stress due to the pandemic. People who call Washington Listens will speak to a support specialist and receive information and connection to community resources in their area. The program is anonymous and no identifying information is maintained. People who staff Washington Listens will receive basic training needed to provide support to individuals during the COVID-19 pandemic. To reach Washington Listens, call 1-833-681-0211. Screen reader compliant factsheet here.

ISLAND COUNTY APPROVED FOR PHASE 3 REOPENING.

On June 19, the Secretary of Health approved the Island County Phase 3 variance request, subject to conditions. With this approval, business services and activities listed in Phase 3 of the Safe Start plan are now permitted, provided appropriate guidelines and safety measures are implemented. In order to remain in compliance with Phase 3, Island County must adhere to the aforementioned conditions, including but not limited to:

• An individual Phase 3 business sector may reopen only AFTER the state publishes its guidelines for the specific sector, or publishes generic phase guidance which applies to all businesses opening in Phase 3. An individual business is only allowed to reopen after it can implement those guidelines. The guidelines can be accessed at https://www.governor.wa.gov/issues/issues/covid-19-resources/covid-19-reopening-
guidance-businesses-and-workers.

• No decisions have been made yet on a timeline for a county moving to Phase 4.

See more https://www.islandcountywa.gov/Health/Pages/COVID-19.aspx

The broad workgroup consisted of more than 100 educators, education leaders, elected officials, community-based organizations, parents, students, and community members.

SWSD survey to parents, staff and students is still open. Please complete the re-opening survey and be heard. The survey link was emailed on Monday June 8th. If you are a staff member, parent or student and did not receive the link, please email communications@sw.wednet.edu.

post_text: Congratulations Orcas! South Whidbey Elementary School was named a Sustaining Bronze certified Washington Green School for the continued efforts in educating the school community about waste reduction practices. The Washington Green School program was especially impressed that SWES was able to expand the recycling program to include markers and broken pencils. Thank you to teacher Lori O'Brien, Jolene Westphal and the Green Team Students who led the way for this accomplishment. Great job ORCAS!!!

Congratulations to South Whidbey HIgh School's Isaiah Giffin who was inducted into the National Technical Honor Society (NTHS) because of his success and accomplishments in the CTE Program – Video Game Design at Sno-Isle TECH Skills Center. Requirements for NTHS Membership include the following:
4.0 grade in the class.
No more than 3 absences 1st semester.
Must display competent character, technical skills, professional ethics, and be safety conscious.

Thursday (5/14) through Saturday 5/16, SWHS will host the Island County Public Health COVID-19 community testing. They will be set up in the SWHS parking lot from 11am -5pm. This testing is by invitation ONLY. To be invited, you must complete the county survey (see more on their website: https://www.islandcountywa.gov/Health/Pages/COVID-19.aspx) Each person that arrives will be checked in to verify that they received an invitation to be tested. Those without an invitation will be exited.

SWSD Grab and Go Meal pick up will still be happening during the testing. However, please watch for signs since the pick up location may need to be moved to a different area of the SWHS parking lot.

If you have any questions about the testing, please call 360.678.2301.

Congratulations to SWSD Teachers Jennifer Gandarias, Sarah Gillett, Laura Spear, Debra Davies-Vogel and Michael Swenson who were selected by the Real Actions Create Equity (R.A.C.E.) Group as the 2020 RACE Champions for their dedication to supporting racial diversity and nurturing racial equity in our schools!

RACE (Real Actions Create Equity), a Readiness to Learn Program, was formed in the spring of 2017 to educate about effective responses to racial and ethnic biases. They raise awareness of the existence of systemic inequity and create safe spaces for people impacted by these injustices.

https://www.readinesstolearn.org/race

Congratulations to South Whidbey School District Special Education on a successful WISM Review!!! OSPI selects districts annually for the WISM (Washington Integrated System of Monitoring) Review. During this process, the district's special education services are rated on the following key elements:
Critical Element I – Data Management
Critical Element II – Fiscal
Critical Element III – Dispute Resolution
Critical Element IV – Policies, Procedures, Practices for Priority Areas
Critical Element V – Individualized Education Program (IEP) Implementation
Our district received no required action in every element. This is outstanding and a reflection of the amazing special educators we have in South Whidbey.

May 5 at 11:05 AM ·

Governor Inslee recently announced his phased plan to reopen Washington State, which includes having better testing. As part of this plan, counties throughout Washington have been instructed to test a large number of people for COVID-19. We need your help to reopen Island County and Washington!
Island County Public Health, WhidbeyHealth, and a variety of other community partners are working together to test a large number of Island County residents for COVID-19. Mobile testing sites will be available throughout the county, beginning the week of May 11.
For additional details and to sign-up for testing, please fill-out the survey on the Island County Public Health COVID-19 page. You can also access the survey directly at https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/GR2COVID19.

Washington Celebrates South Whidbey Elementary, Middle and High Schools During School Recognition Week!

The State Board of Education, the Educational Opportunity Gap Oversight and Accountability Committee (EOGOAC), and the Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction have identified 391 schools state-wide to receive recognition.

Schools in Washington stand out for closing gaps, showing growth, and demonstrating achievement according to new data released by the state. Washington school recognition honors schools that have received support and are thriving, and to highlight positive school systems changes happening all over the state. This year, 391 schools are being recognized. Three of our South Whidbey School District Schools were recognized.

Great job South Whidbey!!!

post_text: WE ARE DOING THIS TOGETHER!!!! Today, our food service provided 427 meals to children in our district. Our school garden is providing veges for the meals and starts for families to begin their home gardens. One of our substitute teachers, Bonni Mattson made about 50 masks for our staff and children. And today, Robbies food truck out of Freeland gave the transportation department freshly made mini donuts as a thank you. The hard work, support, and kindness of the staff and community are appreciated! Thank you so much! We are in this together!

It's time for South Whidbey Elementary Kindergarten Registration. Our goal is to register all prospective kindergarten students during the month of April (April 20th- May 1st) in order to prepare for the 2020-21 school year. Upon registration, you will be contacted with further information.

For online registration beginning Monday, April 20th, go to:
https://www2.nwrdc.wa-k12.net/scripts/cgiip.exe/WService=wswhidbs71/skyenroll

For paper registration, packets are available for pick-up at the main entrance of the K-4 campus, Monday thru Friday, 9-3:30pm. Please call the office with questions at 360.221.4600.

School farmers and families! We have beautiful kale and sour plant (french sorrel) starts, and tasty Makah Ozette potatoes for your garden! They are ready to go in the ground now.

Stay tuned for our lettuce and bok choy starts that will be ready soon.
Sour plant will grown well in a container.

post_text:
Today is Census Day!

Participation in the Census will impact our region and communities for the next decade. Every ten years, the population of the United States is counted in order to determine who receives federal funding and political representation. For every person who is counted in the census, about $2,000 will go to a local program or service per year. If we don’t have everyone counted, other states will get some of our share of federal resources. For more information please visit Island County’s webpage: https://www.islandcountywa.gov/Census/Pages/Home.aspx

The 2020 Census questionnaire is online linked here:https://my2020census.gov/

post_text:
CONGRATULATIONS to SWHS's Natalie Rodriguez whose artwork, “Gaea’s Tears”, was selected as a scholarship award recipient in the NWESD Regional High School Art Show. The online gallery can be viewed here: https://www.nwesd.org/nwesd-regional-high-school-art-show/

Judges were able to visit the art gallery before the Central Washington University office closed and judge the work and the judges from Central Washington University judged through the online gallery. Along with CWU judges NWESD had 3 other local artists come in and judge the students art. NWESD will be submitting Gaea’s Tears to OSPI as one of the state finalists.

Attached is Natalie's winning art piece and a beautiful image of her still life study in the art classroom she did right before we had to close the school. She is truly an exceptional art student. Many of the other art students works were on display in the NWESD online gallery as well. SWSD is so very proud of all the work the art students are doing!

During this time of staying at home, we hope that many more students are working on their art skills at home.

We are working with WIN and the foodbank to assist with food deliveries for families in need. Please contact the Family Resource Center for assistance. 360-221-6808 ext 4321.

post_text: Go fry go!!! Our South Whidbey Elementary School Coho salmon fry were released by some of the South Whidbey Student Salmon Ambassadors into the Maxwelton Creek on Saturday afternoon. About 400 salmon fry were released. Watching them venture out with well wishers cheering them on was truly heartwarming.The fry will spend some time on the creek and then venture out to the Sound and then to the Ocean. In about four years, they will work their way back to the creek in an effort to return and spawn. Thank you to Lori O'brien and the Whidbey Watershed Stewards that make this event possible.

South Whidbey Staff, Students, Families and Community,

South Whidbey School District is CLOSED to students from Monday, March 16th through April 24, 2020.:

Governor Inslee has ordered school districts in King, Pierce and Snohomish counties to close in effort to slow down the transmission of the COVID 19 virus. Given our close proximity to King and Snohomish Counties we are closing as well.

Reasons for this decision include another confirmed case in Island County, the fact that many of our students attend programs at Sno-Isle Skills center in Mukilteo and at Running Start in various locations, and many members of our community commute daily to these counties. A significant number of community members fall within the high risk category including a large number of staff

Please read the email sent for more details. Our website will continue to provide updated information

South Whidbey School District appreciates that this is very difficult and unprecedented time. We are all in this together.

https://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/WAOSPI/bulletins/280dae5

The issues highlighted in LIKE are great conversation starters with your children. (Did you know the average person checks their phone 150 times a day? That's a fact from LIKE.) There will be a facilitated discussion after the Sunday showing to help parents with a technology plan for their families. Lisa Honold, Director of the Center for Online Safety, will lead these discussions and will cover setting up healthy technology goals, managing social media and gaming platforms and talking to kids about the risks and dangers of technology.

post_text:
The SWSD Kitchen and Food Service Advisory Team are taking food service to higher levels. Rachael Mathews and Volunteers (Mary Ann Stine, Breayne Bishop, Sarah Kirkconnell and Laura Bedell) each partner with K-4 PE Teacher, Craig Stelling, on Mondays to present to students on various topics.

The students made their own trail mix on Monday Feb. 24 and talked about moderation, healthy snack ideas and then played a game called "Trail Mix".

On Monday, March 2 they tasted Garlic Rosemary Hummus (Garlic and Rosemary was from our very own Farm). The hummus is now added to the salad bar at lunch time as an alternative to Ranch for dipping their veggies. They also talked about good calories in vs. calories out.

Next up is Smoothie Day where students will get to "guess" what is in their smoothie. They will be using Strawberry, Blueberry, Yogurt and Kale (Kale from the Garden) and talking about how you can get lots of different food groups into a smoothie that is a healthy option to fill you up any time of the day.

If you have children with asthma or other medical conditions that put them at higher risk for an infection, talk to your health care provider now about a plan to protect them during the flu season.

Please plan for childcare at home if your child gets sick. Many families around the country are creating "childcare co-ops" with friends and neighbors. These trusted friends and family work together to share the responsibility of caring for sick children. If you have children with asthma or other medical conditions that put them at higher risk for an infection, talk to your health care provider now about a plan to protect them during the flu season.

NPR has a comic that explores the coronavirus for kids. https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/02/28/809580453/just-for-kids-a-comic-exploring-the-new-coronavirus

post_text: How can I get a book published? Where does inspiration for a story come from? South Whidbey Elementary third graders found out yesterday from author Suzanne Selfors. Ms. Selfors talked about perserverance and showed the students her writings when she was a 3rd grader, then a 6th grader and then an adult. She talked about how many rejection letters she received before publishing her many books. Ms. Selfors has written over thirty books and is best known at SWES for her Wedgie and Gizmo series. 5 lucky kids received autographed copies of one of her books. The visit was sponsored by Sno Isle libraries as part of the Third Grade Reading Challenge . https://www.suzanneselfors.com/

post_text:
The SWES salmon are preparing to "swim up" soon!
"Swimming up" means that they will leave the bottom of the tank and swim to the surface of the water. Instinctively, they will take in air and inflate their swim bladder. It is like a long narrow balloon inside of them just below their spine. It helps them stay afloat and use less energy. Signs that show they are getting ready to "swim up" are: Their yolk sac is almost all the way absorbed. Their skin is growing over their yolk sac. (The term for this is buttoning up. )They have also developed camouflage markings and their fins are fully functioning.
The swimming up milestone will likely happen within the next week. After that, they will no longer need to be protected from light so the silver insulation will come off and the students will slowly introduce food to them.

post_text: “It is expensive to have a child!”, “I had to sell my car to pay my debt” These were just some of the things that SWHS Students learned at the SWHS-BECU Financial Fair. Volunteers helped students in grades 9-12 learn about earning and spending their money between transportation, household, entertainment, clothing and personal care, child care, and financial investments. Students used their phones, tablets or were loaned kindles from school to use during the fair and visit the different booths and make their own choices. Some students learned about overcharges from not paying their debts in time. Some students had money left in the bank at the end of the month and learned the difference between saving and investing. Although the logistics were challenging, the event was a huge success thanks to the hard work of Kayla Phillips, our leadership and CTE/Leadership teacher, BECU and all of the staff and community volunteers that made it possible.

post_text: South Whidbey Students attended STEM Day at Microsoft on Saturday, February 8th. Girls in 5th-8th grade spent the day with inspiring women who are currently working in STEM careers. They were able to ask questions and heard stories about their paths to success as well as the challenges they faced along the way. Teams of students built robots, contemplated the impact of virtual reality and even brainstormed ways technology can help clean water. Our students left feeling empowered and full of curiosity!

post_text:
Random Acts of Kindness Week (RAK) starts on Monday at the Elementary School! Join in!

Monday, Feb. 10th: APPRECIATION DAY
Practice RAK by giving others compliments and appreciations.

Tuesday, Feb. 11th: COURTESY DAY
Show courtesy at school, the store, while waiting for the ferry, or getting that morning cup of coffee.

Wednesday, Feb. 12th: INCLUDE EVERYONE DAY
Today, make a special effort to include everyone. Remember the times that you felt left out and reach out to someone else.

Thursday, Feb. 13th: KINDNESS BEGINS WITH ME DAY
Take time to do something especially for you. You are special!

Friday, Feb. 14th: LET THEM KNOW YOU CARE DAY
Take advantage of RAK week today by calling, writing, or telling someone how much they mean to you. An old friend or family member would love to receive a call or Valentine from you.

Saturday, Feb. 15th: HUG DAY
Celebrate RAK week by giving hugs to others.

Sunday, Feb. 16th: LOVE AND FAMILY DAY
Spend time with your family. Let them know how much you love them.

PASS IT ON....

Have a wonderful RANDOM ACTS OF KINDNESS week everyone!

post_text: SWSD Athletic Trainer Nathan Welever visited South Whidbey Elementary last Friday to teach Ms. Kizer's 4th grade class about head injuries and concussions in youth sports. The kids were taught what happens in the brain with a hit on the head. He brought helmet materials and talked about prevention. Most important, he taught the kids to report their symptoms to adults! Then the class tested their "Egg Helmet" designs to find materials that protect an egghead. The kids were very clever, using air in materials like bubble wrap and protective layers that absorb impacts. Most of the designs worked, too! Thank you Mr. Welever for working to keep all of our kids and athletes safe.

post_text: Today, South Whidbey grades 7-12 had a moving assembly remembering Martin Luther King Jr and learning to fight ignorance from Deputy Tavier Wasser. Deputy Wasser graduated from South Whidbey High School in 2004. After his time with the Marines which included service under President Obama as the security advisor for Marine One, he has returned to Whidbey to raise his family and serve his community. “Racism is a failure to understand each other”. He asked the students not to be ignorant and not to be ok with others being ignorant. Everyone should be free to be themselves without fear of reprimand. We strive to be better and to make the world a better place. SWHS leadership students stressed that non-violence is a powerful social force for transformation. The Foundation is love.

post_text:
South Whidbey Elementary School North and South Campuses remembered Martin Luther King Jr with two assemblies. The K-4 assembly had 400 little voices singing "We Shall Overcome" and "If I had a hammer". The 5-6 assembly included marimba, poems and quotes from Martin Luther King Jr, and a skit from the Real Action for Change and Equity group that focused on I AM THE DREAM, WE ARE THE DREAM, I HAVE A DREAM, LET'S LIVE THE DREAM.
"Time is always right to do what is right" - MLKjr
